%N A034173 a(n) is minimal such that prime factorizations of a(n), ..., a(n)+n-1 have same exponents.
%C A034173 a(8) > 10^13. - _Donovan Johnson_, Oct 20 2009
%C A034173 _Don Reble_ has shown that a(8) < 1.9*10^42, cf. link.
%C A034173 From _David Wasserman_, Jan 05 2019: (Start)
%C A034173 a(8) <= 108111092880293127811946663766147737122,
%C A034173 a(9) <= 6850672946809600696044301071559918192380244,
%C A034173 a(10) <= 96037988156124494415303285590850571857698741869620,
%C A034173 a(11) <= 9044737840075556371215937303485030235666252755947862558252154847122. (End)
%C A034173 Dickson's conjecture implies that this sequence is infinite. Sketch of proof: To find n consecutive natural numbers with the same prime signature, let x be the first of these numbers. We specify x modulo various prime powers in order to determine factors of the numbers x through x + n - 1. To determine a factor p with multiplicity exactly i, we specify x modulo p^(i + 1). Start with primes <= n, and add primes until x through x + n - 1 all have known factors with the same prime signature. By the Chinese Remainder Theorem, there are numbers y, m, and d_0 through d_(n - 1) such that (1) d_0 through d_(n - 1) all have the same prime signature, (2) for any integers 0 <= i < n and k >= 0, (2a) y + k*m + i is divisible by d_i, and (2b) (y + k*m + i)/d_i is relatively prime to m. Consider the n linear forms (y + i)/d_i + k*(m/d_i). To apply Dickson's conjecture, we must show that for every prime p, there is a k such that none of the forms are divisible by p. For p that divides m, this is true for all k by (2b). For p not dividing m, this is true because p > n and for each form, p divides it for only one k modulo p. The conjecture implies that there's a k for which all n forms are primes p_0, ..., p_(n - 1) that don't divide m. Then p_0*d_0, ..., p_(n - 1)*d_(n - 1) are consecutive integers with the same prime signature. - _David Wasserman_, Mar 15 2026
%C A034173 a(12) <= 3758581019003538722881879725203205366049807290228996281308524895932866. - _David Wasserman_, Apr 26 2026
%H A034173 Don Reble, <a href="/A034173/a034173.txt">A034173(8) exists</a>, SeqFan list, Oct 23 2012.
%F A034173 a(n) = A034174(n) - n + 1. - _Max Alekseyev_, Nov 10 2009
%F A034173 a(n) = A083785(n,1) = A113456(1,n); a(2) = A052213(1), a(3) = A052214(1), a(4) = A175590(1), a(5) = A218448(1), a(6) = A218448(62) = A218448(63)-1. - _M. F. Hasler_, Oct 28 2012
%F A034173 a(6) = A218455(1); a(7) = A218865(1) = A218455(443) = A218455(444)-1. - _M. F. Hasler_, Apr 27 2026
%e A034173 a(4) = 19940 because 19940, ..., 19943 all have the form p^2 q r.
%e A034173 From _M. F. Hasler_, Apr 27 2026: (Start)
%e A034173 The first few terms, with their factorization and prime signature (equal to that of the next n-1 numbers), are as follows:
%e A034173    n |     a(n)     = (factorization)            | prime signature
%e A034173   ---+-------------------------------------------+----------------
%e A034173    1 |       1      = empty product              | {}
%e A034173    2 |       2      = 2                          | {1}
%e A034173    3 |      33      = 3 * 11                     | {1,1}
%e A034173    4 |     19940    = 2^2 * 5 * 997              | {2,1,1}
%e A034173    5 |    204323    = 7 * 17^2 * 101             | {2,1,1}
%e A034173    6 |   380480345  = 5 * 7^2 * 1552981          | {2,1,1}
%e A034173    7 | 440738966073 = 3 * 7^2 * 1213 * 2471743   | {2,1,1,1}
%e A034173 (End)
%o A034173 (PARI)
%o A034173 is_bad(k,n)=my(s(k)=vecsort(factor(k)[,2]), f=s(k+=n-1));for(i=1,n-1, f==(f=s(k--))|| return(n-i)) /* Returns the distance to the next candidate k, 0 means k is a valid solution. - _M. F. Hasler_, Oct 23 2012, refactored Apr 27 2026 */
%o A034173 {A034173(n,k=1,j=0)=while(j=is_bad(k+=j,n),);k} \\ Can be given a starting value k > 1 for the search as 2nd optional arg, for example k = a(n-1). Returns a valid k equal to a(n) if there is no smaller solution. - Refactored from 2012 code by _M. F. Hasler_, Apr 27 2026
%Y A034173 Cf. A034174.
%Y A034173 Cf. A006558, A083790.
%Y A034173 Cf. A052213, A052214, A175590, A218448, A218455, A218865. This sequence is the first column of A083785 and first row of A113456. The latter generalizes to arithmetic progressions with step d >= 1. - _M. F. Hasler_, Oct 28 2012
